{{redirect|4004 BC|the Biblically based estimate of the creation of the Earth|Ussher chronology}} {{Millenniumbox|-5}}{{Neolithic}}
The '''5th millennium BC''' spanned the years 5000 through 4001 BC. It saw the spread of [[agriculture]] from [[Western Asia]] throughout [[Southern Europe|Southern]] and [[Central Europe]].
Urban cultures in [[Mesopotamia]] and [[Anatolia]] flourished, developing the [[wheel]]. [[Copper]] ornaments became more common, marking the beginning of the [[Chalcolithic]]. [[Animal husbandry]] spread throughout [[Eurasia]], reaching [[China]].
[[World population estimates|World population]] growth relaxes after the burst due to the [[Neolithic Revolution]]. World population is largely stable, at roughly 40 million, with a slow overall growth rate at roughly 0.03% p.a.<ref>Jean-Noël Biraben, "Essai sur l'évolution du nombre des hommes", ''Population'' 34-1 (1979), 13-25, estimates 40 million at 5000 BC and 100 million at 1600 BC, for an average growth rate of 0.027% p.a. over the Chalcolithic to Middle Bronze Age.</ref>
