{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Use British English|date=September 2017}} [[File:Coat of Arms of the Court of the Lord Lyon.svg|thumb|250px|right|[[Lord Lyon King of Arms|Lord Lyon]]'s official [[coat of arms]]]]
'''William David Hamilton Sellar''', [[Member of the Royal Victorian Order|MVO]], [[Master of Arts|MA]], [[LLB]], [[FRHistS]], [[FSA (Scot)]] (born 27 February 1941) served as [[Lord Lyon King of Arms]] from 2008 to 2014. He is married, with three adult sons and a step-son.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} [[File:RVO-Star (MVO).jpg|thumb|left|90px| MVO insignia]] Sellar read history at [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]] graduating as [[Bachelor of Arts]] before gaining a law degree ([[LLB]]) from the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.ed.ac.uk/people/wdavidhsellar|title=www.law.ed.ac.uk|publisher=}}</ref> He qualified as a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] solicitor in 1966, and after two years as a legal assessor with the Scottish Land Court joined in 1968 the [[University of Edinburgh School of Law|Faculty of Law]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]], where he has been elected an Honorary Fellow.
Sellar has written about the [[Lord of the Isles|Lordship of the Isles]] and on the origins of many [[Highland]] families.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bill.celt.dias.ie/vol4/author.php?AuthorID=1395|title=Sellar (William David Hamilton)|website=bill.celt.dias.ie}}</ref>
He has served as a Member of the [[Ancient Monuments Board for Scotland]], on the Councils of the Scottish [[Family history society|Genealogy Society]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsgenealogy.com/|title=Scottish Genealogy Society Edinburgh - The society for Scottish family history|first=The Scottish Genealogy Society - Family History and Ancestry in|last=Scotland|website=www.scotsgenealogy.com}}</ref> and the [[Heraldry Society of Scotland]], and as Vice-President of the [[Society of Antiquaries of Scotland]]. He was the O'Donnell Lecturer, in Celtic Studues, at Edinburgh in 1985 and the Rhind Lecturer for the Society of Antiquaries in 2000. He held the office of [[Bute Pursuivant|Bute Pursuivant of Arms]] from 2001 until his appointment in 2008 as Lord Lyon King of Arms.<ref>{{Edinburgh Gazette |issue=25116 |date=9 November 2001 |page=2663 |city=e }}</ref>
A Fellow of the [[Society of Antiquaries of Scotland]] (FSA Scot) and a [[Fellow of the Royal Historical Society]] (FRHistS),<ref>[http://www.royalhistoricalsociety.org/rhsfellows.php www.royalhistoricalsociety.org] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827093607/http://www.royalhistoricalsociety.org/rhsfellows.php |date=27 August 2012 }}</ref> Sellar was appointed [[Member of the Royal Victorian Order]] (MVO) in the 2014 New Year Honours<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=60728 |supp=y|page=4|date=31 December 2013}}</ref> in anticipation of his retirement from the office of Lord Lyon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/lord-lyon-to-retire-at-end-of-January|title=2014.22455442 www.heraldscotland.com|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/honours-list/10542766/New-Year-Honours-2014-list-in-full.html|title=New Year Honours 2014: list in full|date=2013-12-30|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>
