{{BLP sources|date=February 2015}} {{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox academic | name = R.&nbsp;I. Moore | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRHistS|size=100%}} | image = | alt = | birth_name = Robert Ian Moore | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1941|05|08}} | birth_place = [[Enniskillen]], Northern Ireland | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | residence = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], England | nationality = British | other_names = Bob Moore | spouse = | website = {{official URL}} | alma_mater = [[Merton College, Oxford]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | school_tradition = | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | influences = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | discipline = History | sub_discipline = [[Medieval history]] | workplaces = {{unbulleted list | [[University of Sheffield]] | [[Newcastle University]]}} | doctoral_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | notable_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = {{hlist | History of [[heresy]] | [[comparative history|comparative]] [[world history]]}} | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influenced = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | signature = | signature_alt = }} '''Robert Ian''' "'''Bob'''" '''Moore''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRHistS}} (born 1941),<ref name="MCreg">{{cite book|editor1-last=Levens|editor1-first=R.&nbsp;G.&nbsp;C.|title=Merton College Register 1900–1964|date=1964|publisher=Basil Blackwell|location=Oxford|page=516}}</ref> most commonly known as '''R.&nbsp;I. Moore''', is a British historian who is Professor Emeritus of History at [[Newcastle University]]. He specialises in [[medieval history]] and has written several influential works on the subject of [[heresy]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.brill.nl/heresy-and-persecuting-society-middle-ages|title=Heresy and the persecuting society in the Middle Age: Essays on the work of R.&nbsp;I. Moore|publisher=Brill|year=2006|issn=1573-5664|isbn=9789004150980|editor=Frassetto, Michael}}</ref> Moore was a pioneer in the UK of the teaching of [[world history]] to [[undergraduate]] students, has published numerous papers on [[comparative history|comparative]] world history, and is series editor of the Blackwell History of the World.
==Biography== Moore was born in [[Enniskillen]], Northern Ireland, on 8 May 1941. He studied at [[Merton College, Oxford]], from which he received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1962<ref name=MCreg /> and a [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Master of Arts]] degree in 1966. From 1964 to 1994 he taught medieval history at the [[University of Sheffield]], then moving to the [[Newcastle University]], where he remained until 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=Emeritus Professor Robert Moore|url=http://www.ncl.ac.uk/historical/staff/profile/r.i.moore|website=School of History, Classics and Archaeology|publisher=Newcastle University|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref> He was a visiting professor at the [[University of Chicago]] in 1989 and the [[University of California at Berkeley]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Visiting Scholars|url=http://medieval.berkeley.edu/people/visiting-scholars|website=Program in medieval studies, University of California, Berkeley|publisher=Regents of the University of California|accessdate=18 March 2016}}</ref>
