'''Valentin Mikhaylovich Alekseyev''' ({{lang-ru|Валентин Михайлович Алексеев}}) (1924 – 1994) was a Soviet [[historian]] from [[St.Petersburg]]. His major works could not pass [[Censorship in the Soviet Union|censorship]] during the [[Soviet times]] and their publications began only during the ''[[perestroika]]'' times, although they have been circulating in ''[[samizdat]]''.<ref name="PCh">[[Peter Cheremushkin]], ''[http://www.sipa.columbia.edu/ece/vol5no3/ruspol.pdf Russian-Polish Relations: A Long Way From Stereotypes to Reconciliation]'', ''InterMarium'' Vol. 5 (2002)</ref><ref>[http://www.memo.ru/history/getto/preface.htm "Life and Books of Valentin Alekseyev"], the preface to the book ''The Warsaw Ghetto No Longer Exists'' {{ru icon}}</ref>

The Hungarian government awarded Alekseyev with the [[Imre Nagy Medal]] for his book ''Hungary-56''.<ref>[http://www.panrus.com/books/details.php?langID=1&bookID=5468 "Humgary-56", book profile]</ref>

